settings.tab-text:
Each day includes breakfast, lunch, dinner, snacks, teas, lattes, and/or broths to supplement and support all regular meals.

Add your partner and they'll receive Breakfast, Lunch, & Dinner each day alongside your plan.

Check out our sample menu and meal plan options to gain greater insight to what’s included with your order.

Simply create your custom meal plan, choose your dietary preference, share your estimated due date, and include any other important notes you may have.

Exact birth dates are hard to plan. Baby arrives when baby arrives. You'll receive an informational email on how and when to schedule your first delivery. You can reach out to us whenever you are ready to begin.

Refer to our FAQs or get in touch if you have any ordering questions!

We deliver on Sundays, Tuesdays, & Thursdays for optimal freshness. We’ll notify you of your personal delivery schedule.

Your delivery will include instructions on reheating and daily distribution of items.

As soon as you get your delivered goods place all items in your fridge and/or begin reheating!

Our delivery containers consist of glass jars and BPA-free lids. Your delivery comes in a recyclable box with a premium non-toxic and biodegradable drain-safe ice pack to keep food fresh.

For sustainability purposes we ask you to return all glass jars to us by placing the jars from the previous delivery in your most recently received box with ice packs on your doorstep for our drivers to pick up at the time of your next delivery and bring back for our team to sanitize and reuse. After your final delivery, we offer a final pick up service!

All Milky Oat products require refrigeration. These refrigerated items must be kept at a temperature of 41 degrees F or below.

Microwave Reheat Instructions: All items may be microwaved using a microwave safe plate or bowl on High for 45 seconds - 1 minute. Individual microwaves may vary. Always check temperature as food items may be very hot or need further heating.

Stovetop Reheat Instructions: All items may be reheated on the stove top with an appropriate pot or pan and stirred to bring up to temperature. Soups, stews, and porridges may need an additional splash of water as stirred to loosen.

Don’t sweat the details. We’ll provide reheat instructions with your delivery. These first weeks with your new baby are all we want you focused on, as well as your own recovery, of course!

Made with love, our menu is always shifting depending on what our local purveyors have in season. Our mission is to provide you with the finest organic meals that include the most nutritious ingredients for optimal recovery. Check out our Key Nutrients and Ingredient Highlights sections below to learn more about our devotion to the food we prepare.

You will never find any refined sugars, gluten, preservatives, peanuts, dairy, or genetically modified ingredients on our menu.

settings.subtitle: How it Works
settings.title: The first six weeks after childbirth is a key window of time for nourishment and restoration for the mother.
settings.text:
Ancient wisdom traditions believe that the first 42 days after birth can impact the next 42 years. Modern studies focus on the positive impact of implementing certain nutrients to curb postpartum depletion.

We believe food has the capacity to heal. Influenced by cultures around the globe alongside respect for the science supporting proper nutrient intake, we provide essential nourishment for the weeks after childbirth so that you may restore.

settings.title: Protein
settings.content: Protein is essential for rebuilding the muscles and cells. We design many of our meals around protein-rich legumes, oats, meats, fish, eggs, nuts, seeds, and ancient grains.

settings.title: Vitamin A
settings.content: Vitamin A is important for both visual health and immune function. The World Health Organization recommends a diet rich in Vitamin A for breastfeeding mothers. Found in foods such as eggs, liver, salmon, and mackerel.

settings.title: Vitamin C
settings.content: Vitamin C supports a healthy immune system. We provide our mothers with Vitamin C by including foods such as citrus, strawberries, currants, goji berries, and potatoes.

settings.title: Vitamin D
settings.content: Vitamin D supports a healthy brain, nervous system, and immune system. It can reduce the risk of postpartum depression and anxiety. Found in salmon, liver, and egg yolks.

settings.title: DHA
settings.content: DHA is an important Omega-3 fatty acid which can improve brain and vision development in breastfed babies and plays a role in reducing inflammation and postpartum depression in mothers. Found in salmon, sardines, eggs, and seaweed.

settings.title: Folate
settings.content: Folate is needed for production of white and red blood cells and for brain development in breastfeeding babies. Found in broccoli, brussels sprouts, leafy greens, peas, chickpeas, and liver.

settings.title: Niacin
settings.content: Niacin has been found to alleviate postpartum depression, improve skin health, and boost brain function. Found in foods such as liver, chicken, turkey, salmon, anchovies, pork, beef, avocado, brown rice, mushrooms, peas, and potatoes.

settings.title: Vitamin B12
settings.content: Vitamin B12 is necessary for proper red blood cell development and energy production. Goodbye, fatigue! Found in clams, mussels, salmon, beef, and lamb. For breastfeeding vegan/vegetarian mothers, the CDC recommends supplementing B12.

settings.title: Iodine
settings.content: Iodine is a trace mineral which supports the thyroid in hormone synthesis. The World Health Organization recommends increasing iodine intake during prenatal and postpartum periods. Found in eggs and seafood.

settings.title: Iron
settings.content: It’s important to replenish the body’s iron stores after natural blood and iron loss during pregnancy and childbirth. Breastfeeding mothers need higher iron as it is needed to support both their own bodies and their babies’ development. Red meat, liver, oysters, and leafy greens can all provide mothers with the iron they need. Vegans and vegetarians should check in with your healthcare provider about supplementing additional iron.

settings.title: Magnesium
settings.content: Magnesium can support healthy muscle contraction, alleviate anxiety, and encourage healthy bowel movements. Found in nuts, seeds, legumes, quinoa, dark chocolate, and spinach.

settings.title: Zinc
settings.content: Zinc supports the body's ability to absorb and metabolize important micronutrients like Vitamin A. It may also help with postpartum depression. Found in oysters, red meat, poultry, nuts, seeds, and legumes.
